<div class="header"><h1>msg and dsg soluability breakdown (20251222)</h1></div>
<div class="body">
<p>Prompt: MSG and DSG are soluable. how much is left over?</p>
<p><strong>Short answer:</strong> essentially none.</p>

<p>MSG (monosodium glutamate) and DSG (disodium guanylate) are both highly water-soluble salts. If they are fully dissolved, there is no solid material left over.</p>

<p>When added below their solubility limits, they dissolve completely at the molecular/ionic level. In that state, there is nothing that can be filtered, settled, or weighed.</p>

<p><strong>Situations where something may remain:</strong></p>

<ul>
  <li><strong>Oversaturation:</strong> If more MSG or DSG is added than the water can dissolve, the excess remains as undissolved solid.</li>
  <li><strong>Trace impurities:</strong> Very small amounts of manufacturing impurities may be present, typically at parts-per-million levels.</li>
  <li><strong>Evaporation:</strong> If water evaporates, the dissolved MSG and DSG will recrystallize. This is due to concentration changes, not incomplete solubility.</li>
</ul>

<p><strong>Bottom line:</strong> if the solution is not oversaturated, the amount “left over” after dissolution is effectively zero.</p>

</div>
